{
  "doc_id": "12471",
  "text": "An intriguing finding in the present study was that following the marathon training brachial IMT in the experimental group, when statistically adjusted for multiple comparisons, trended toward significance (p = 0.032) while popliteal IMT remained unchanged (p = 0.260). This result is in contrast with data presented by others [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] showing that IMT decreased in the trained limb as a result of exercise training. It is possible that the discrepancy is due to localized inflammation in the lower extremities associated with a relatively high volume of training (i.e., 36 total miles, inclusive of an 18 mile run) that occurred during the week prior to data collection. In response to this training load, the participants may have experienced sufficient micro-trauma in the legs to stimulate localized inflammation. This explanation is supported by limited data [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] and constitutes an area of research that has been identified as one in need of further investigation [CITATION_6] .",
